      <body>
         <div type="entry">
                <head>Vaschalde, Arthur Adolphe, C.S.B.</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Vaschalde-Arthur-Adolphe-CSB</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/580</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">571</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="423-424"/>
                    <idno type="althead" subtype="altorder">Arthur Adolphe Vaschalde, C.S.B.</idno>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/803</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Syriac scholar at the Catholic University of America.
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(1871– 1942)</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Vaschalde’s Syriac career flourished at The Catholic University of America
                        (CUA) where he received a <choice>
                            <sic>Ph. D.</sic>
                            <corr>Ph.D.</corr>
                        </choice> in 1901. His dissertation, an edition,
                        translation, and study of three letters of <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Philoxenos-of-Mabbug">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/44">Philoxenos
                            of Mabbug</persName>
                        </ref>, was published in 1902. Vaschalde taught Syriac and
                        Coptic at CUA from 1910 to 1939. His work on the Coptic versions of the
                        Bible remains an important resource for scholars today. In 1930 he became
                        the editor for the Coptic section of the Corpus Scriptorum Christianorum
                        Orientalium (<abbr>CSCO</abbr>). Most of his Syriac publications appear in this series,
                        including editions and translations of writings of Philoxenos of Mabbug,
                            <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Babai-the-Great">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/359">Babai the Great</persName>
                        </ref>, <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Yaqub-of-Edessa">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/113">Yaʿqub of
                            Edessa</persName>
                        </ref>, and <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Dionysios-bar-Salibi">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/212">Dionysios
                            bar Ṣalibi</persName>
                        </ref>.</p>
                </div>
